OROPOUCHE AND MAYARO VIRUSES - BRAZIL: (ACRE)
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Wed 3 Jan 2024
Source: G1 [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://tinyurl.com/bp58b6zz>


Acre reached 60 confirmed cases of Oropouche and Mayaro infections,
detected in 10 municipalities in the last month of 2023. According to
data provided to G1 by the Acre State Department of Health (Sesacre),
the state reached 60 cases by 2 Dec 2023.

As a result, Acre recorded an increase in relation to the first total
released by Sesacre in November last year [2023]. Up to then, there
were 6 cities with confirmed cases, with 48 recorded cases in total.

The first registered cases of these infections occurred in April
[2023]. According to the survey, the cases were detected in the
following municipalities.

Oropouche:
Location / No. cases
--------------------
Acrel=E2ndia / 8
Brasil=E9ia / 1
Feij=F3 / 3 (does not appear in the first total count)
Manoel Urbano / 8 (+5 cases)
Porto Acre / 5
Rio Branco / 32
Sena Madureira / 1

Mayaro:
Location / No. cases
--------------------
Cruzeiro do Sul / 3
M=E2ncio Lima / 1 (does not appear in the first total count)
Rio Branco / 1

The 2 viruses cause symptoms similar to those of dengue, transmitted
by the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito. Mayaro is even called chikungunya's
"cousin." (See the symptoms below).

Oropouche fever is an arbovirus, that is, a virus transmitted by
mosquitoes, which presents symptoms similar to dengue, although with a
much lower risk of bleeding complications and death. Rarely, cases may
be complicated by viral (benign) meningitis. The main mosquito that
transmits the disease among humans is _Culicoides paraensis_, better
known as "maruim." Preventive measures consist of avoiding their
proliferation of and contact with these mosquitoes, similar to
precautions against dengue fever.

Mayaro is endemic (has a continuous presence) in Amazonia and is
normally transmitted by mosquitoes of the _Haemagogus_ genus, which
live in the forests and are also known for spreading sylvan [forest]
yellow fever. It is a different profile from _Aedes aegypti_, the
vector of dengue, zika, chikungunya and urban yellow fever -- as it
lives in cities.

"They are febrile syndromes and are very similar to the symptoms of
dengue, with fever, body pain, pain behind the eyes and we are
noticing that there are cases with symptoms on the skin. People are
appearing with spots on the skin too. The exam only showed negative
for dengue and we decided to test the differential diagnosis, as we
call it," explained the head of the Health Surveillance Department,
Edvan Meneses, at the time of the release of the first report.

The coordinator highlighted that Acre had not recorded cases of the
virus in the urban areas for a long time. He highlighted that the
cases were found more in rural areas, and explained the possible
reasons for the locality of infections. "It could be due to the fact
that the city is deeper into the forest, but also due to changes in
the mosquito's life cycle. Now, we are realizing that there are more
houses, we saw that a lot of people went hunting [in the forest], as
is the case with yellow fever. This is surprising for us to notice
[cases] in urban areas, where we find more dengue, zika and
chikungunya," he confirmed.

Because of the lack of confirmation in urban areas, the coordinator
said that the Ministry of Health did not send samples for tests. "We
couldn't know in a broad sense because we didn't test because it
wasn't [recognized as] an endemic disease here. We may have had cases,
but they were underreported due to lack of testing," he said.

With the new recorded cases, the specialist said that a reorganization
of the health network will be carried out with training of
professionals, lectures and alerts about viruses to begin the work of
raising awareness and combating infections.

"They were isolated cases; we didn't have that number of cases in the
urban area. It's not a new disease, but it wasn't in our area. We're
going to train the entire network about Mayaro and Oropouche, even the
names are difficult, so it's a whole movement for training our
network, reorganization, leaving the diagnosis to the units, the
medication and it was something we were not expecting. There are 2
more arboviruses for us to work on during this epidemiological
period," he said.

Symptoms
--------
Oropouche virus [infection]:
- Fever
- Headache
- Pain in the body and joints
- In some cases, the patient may experience vomiting

Mayaro virus [infection]:
- Fever
- Headache
- Body and joint pain
- In some cases, the patient may experience vomiting

The infection generates symptoms similar to those caused by
chikungunya [virus infection], such as high fever and joint pain,
which makes diagnosis difficult.

