[Given the large numbers of dengue cases in Brazil and the recent
chikungunya  and Zika virus outbreaks there, it is not surprising that
these 3 viruses probably have been the default diagnosis in febrile
cases, often without laboratory confirmation, as the above report
mentions. The result is that Oropouche and Mayaro virus infections are
almost certainly underreported not only in Brazil but in the tropical
Americas where the respective arthropod vectors occur.

Oropouche virus [OROV] is endemic in the Amazon Basin, and human cases
have been documented in Brazil, Peru, Ecuador, Panama, and Trinidad
and Tobago. Reports of cases in these countries have been sporadic but
likely underdiagnosed. Because fever with a rash is typical of dengue
fever, yellow fever, chikungunya, and Zika virus infections, timely
laboratory support is essential to make a differential diagnosis.

Although _Culicoides paraensis_, the vector of Oropouche virus, occurs
from the northern USA to Argentina, human cases have been recognized
only in the Amazon Basin and Trinidad and Tobago. One wonders if there
is a possibility that cases are occurring in other countries where
this vector midge is found, but go undiagnosed or misdiagnosed as
dengue fever, yellow fever, chikungunya, or Zika virus infections.
Perhaps OROV diagnostic capability in all tropical areas where the
vector occurs would reveal more cases.

An image of _Culicoides paraensis_ can be seen at
<http://tinyurl.com/ycy4pwrc>.

Mayaro virus (MAYV) is endemic in Brazil. It has been found to cause
human disease in Par=E1 state and in other areas in Brazil. The first
report of Mayaro virus cases was in 1955, in an outbreak in Par=E1
state, Brazil. In 2011, thousands of cases of Mayaro fever were
reported in an outbreak that occurred in Manaus, Amazonas, Brazil.

As Mod.JT noted in an early ProMED post (20110220.0557), MAYV, of the
_Alphavirus_ genus, Togaviridae family, is endemic in tropical areas
of South America (Trinidad, Suriname, French Guyana, Brazil, Peru,
Bolivia, and Venezuela). In 2016, a MAYV infection occurred in a child
in Haiti. The transmission cycle is very similar to that of the yellow
fever virus, using primates as reservoirs and _Haemagogus_ mosquitoes
as vectors.

MAYV has been associated with a variety of mosquitoes that are
possible vectors that can transmit it to humans. MAYV has been
isolated from _Aedes aegypti_ and _Culex quinquefasciatus_ captured in
the field in Brazil. _Anopheles_ mosquitoes have been implicated as
important virus vectors (see references below).

References
----------
1. Brustolin M, Pujhari S, Henderson CA, Rasgon JL. _Anopheles_
mosquitoes may drive invasion and transmission of Mayaro virus across
geographically diverse regions. PLoS Negl Trop Dis. 2018; 12(11):
e0006895; <https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pntd.0006895>
2. Serra OP, Cardoso BF, Ribeiro AL, et al. Mayaro virus and dengue
virus 1 and 4 natural infection in culicids from Cuiaba, state of Mato
Grosso, Brazil. Mem Inst Oswaldo Cruz. 2016; 111(1): 20-9;
<http://dx.doi.org/10.1590/0074-02760150270>

The steps being taken in Acre state, mentioned above, should help
define the extent and incidence of infections by Oropouche and Mayaro
viruses in that state. - Mod.TY

