55rM">http://tinyurl.com/bp58b6zz</a>=0D<br>=0D<br>=0D<br>Acre reached 60 c=
onfirmed cases of Oropouche and Mayaro infections,<br>detected in 10 munici=
palities in the last month of 2023. According to<br>data provided to G1 by =
the Acre State Department of Health (Sesacre),<br>the state reached 60 case=
s by 2 Dec 2023.=0D<br>=0D<br>As a result, Acre recorded an increase in rel=
ation to the first total<br>released by Sesacre in November last year [2023=
]. Up to then, there<br>were 6 cities with confirmed cases, with 48 recorde=
d cases in total.=0D<br>=0D<br>The first registered cases of these infectio=
ns occurred in April<br>[2023]. According to the survey, the cases were det=
ected in the<br>following municipalities.=0D<br>=0D<br>Oropouche:=0D<br>Loc=
ation / No. cases=0D<br>--------------------=0D<br>Acrel=E2ndia / 8=0D<br>B=
rasil=E9ia / 1=0D<br>Feij=F3 / 3 (does not appear in the first total count)=0D=
<br>Manoel Urbano / 8 (+5 cases)=0D<br>Porto Acre / 5=0D<br>Rio Branco / 32=0D=
<br>Sena Madureira / 1=0D<br>=0D<br>Mayaro:=0D<br>Location / No. cases=0D<b=
r>--------------------=0D<br>Cruzeiro do Sul / 3=0D<br>M=E2ncio Lima / 1 (d=
oes not appear in the first total count)=0D<br>Rio Branco / 1=0D<br>=0D<br>=
The 2 viruses cause symptoms similar to those of dengue, transmitted<br>by =
the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito. Mayaro is even called chikungunya's<br>"cousi=
n." (See the symptoms below).=0D<br>=0D<br>Oropouche fever is an arbovirus,=
 that is, a virus transmitted by<br>mosquitoes, which presents symptoms sim=
ilar to dengue, although with a<br>much lower risk of bleeding complication=
s and death. Rarely, cases may<br>be complicated by viral (benign) meningit=
is. The main mosquito that<br>transmits the disease among humans is _Culico=
ides paraensis_, better<br>known as "maruim." Preventive measures consist o=
f avoiding their<br>proliferation of and contact with these mosquitoes, sim=
ilar to<br>precautions against dengue fever.=0D<br>=0D<br>Mayaro is endemic=
 (has a continuous presence) in Amazonia and is<br>normally transmitted by =
mosquitoes of the _Haemagogus_ genus, which<br>live in the forests and are =
also known for spreading sylvan [forest]<br>yellow fever. It is a different=
 profile from _Aedes aegypti_, the<br>vector of dengue, zika, chikungunya a=
nd urban yellow fever -- as it<br>lives in cities.=0D<br>=0D<br>"They are f=
ebrile syndromes and are very similar to the symptoms of<br>dengue, with fe=
ver, body pain, pain behind the eyes and we are<br>noticing that there are =
cases with symptoms on the skin. People are<br>appearing with spots on the =
skin too. The exam only showed negative<br>for dengue and we decided to tes=
t the differential diagnosis, as we<br>call it," explained the head of the =
Health Surveillance Department,<br>Edvan Meneses, at the time of the releas=
e of the first report.=0D<br>=0D<br>The coordinator highlighted that Acre h=
ad not recorded cases of the<br>virus in the urban areas for a long time. H=
e highlighted that the<br>cases were found more in rural areas, and explain=
ed the possible<br>reasons for the locality of infections. "It could be due=
 to the fact<br>that the city is deeper into the forest, but also due to ch=
anges in<br>the mosquito's life cycle. Now, we are realizing that there are=
 more<br>houses, we saw that a lot of people went hunting [in the forest], =
as<br>is the case with yellow fever. This is surprising for us to notice<br=
>[cases] in urban areas, where we find more dengue, zika and<br>chikungunya=
," he confirmed.=0D<br>=0D<br>Because of the lack of confirmation in urban =
areas, the coordinator<br>said that the Ministry of Health did not send sam=
ples for tests. "We<br>couldn't know in a broad sense because we didn't tes=
t because it<br>wasn't [recognized as] an endemic disease here. We may have=
 had cases,<br>but they were underreported due to lack of testing," he said=
.=0D<br>=0D<br>With the new recorded cases, the specialist said that a reor=
ganization<br>of the health network will be carried out with training of<br=
>professionals, lectures and alerts about viruses to begin the work of<br>r=
aising awareness and combating infections.=0D<br>=0D<br>"They were isolated=
 cases; we didn't have that number of cases in the<br>urban area. It's not =
a new disease, but it wasn't in our area. We're<br>going to train the entir=
e network about Mayaro and Oropouche, even the<br>names are difficult, so i=
t's a whole movement for training our<br>network, reorganization, leaving t=
he diagnosis to the units, the<br>medication and it was something we were n=
ot expecting. There are 2<br>more arboviruses for us to work on during this=
 epidemiological<br>period," he said.=0D<br>=0D<br>Symptoms=0D<br>--------=0D=
<br>Oropouche virus [infection]:=0D<br>- Fever=0D<br>- Headache=0D<br>- Pai=
n in the body and joints=0D<br>- In some cases, the patient may experience =
vomiting=0D<br>=0D<br>Mayaro virus [infection]:=0D<br>- Fever=0D<br>- Heada=
che=0D<br>- Body and joint pain=0D<br>- In some cases, the patient may expe=
rience vomiting=0D<br>=0D<br>The infection generates symptoms similar to th=
ose caused by<br>chikungunya [virus infection], such as high fever and join=
t pain,<br>which makes diagnosis difficult.=0D<br>=0D<br>[Byline: Victor Le=
bre]=0D<br>=0D<br>--=0D<br>Communicated by:=0D<br>ProMED<br><br>[Given the =
large numbers of dengue cases in Brazil and the recent<br>chikungunya  and =
Zika virus outbreaks there, it is not surprising that<br>these 3 viruses pr=
obably have been the default diagnosis in febrile<br>cases, often without l=
aboratory confirmation, as the above report<br>mentions. The result is that=
 Oropouche and Mayaro virus infections are<br>almost certainly underreporte=
d not only in Brazil but in the tropical<br>Americas where the respective a=
rthropod vectors occur.=0D<br>=0D<br>Oropouche virus [OROV] is endemic in t=
he Amazon Basin, and human cases<br>have been documented in Brazil, Peru, E=
cuador, Panama, and Trinidad<br>and Tobago. Reports of cases in these count=
ries have been sporadic but<br>likely underdiagnosed. Because fever with a =
rash is typical of dengue<br>fever, yellow fever, chikungunya, and Zika vir=
us infections, timely<br>laboratory support is essential to make a differen=
tial diagnosis.=0D<br>=0D<br>Although _Culicoides paraensis_, the vector of=
 Oropouche virus, occurs<br>from the northern USA to Argentina, human cases=
 have been recognized<br>only in the Amazon Basin and Trinidad and Tobago. =
One wonders if there<br>is a possibility that cases are occurring in other =
countries where<br>this vector midge is found, but go undiagnosed or misdia=
gnosed as<br>dengue fever, yellow fever, chikungunya, or Zika virus infecti=
ons.<br>Perhaps OROV diagnostic capability in all tropical areas where the<=
br>vector occurs would reveal more cases.=0D<br>=0D<br>An image of _Culicoi=
des paraensis_ can be seen at<br><a href=3D"https://u19268662.ct.sendgrid.n=
et/ss/c/DgIMzhc9xO6P0drrFfDxwb4vnlWByeIK_Yi9mBw2IfAspAUSHSELr5hiN1Qqp0Wn/42=
u/zw3J8cCoRUeHcluotqQRqw/h3/zVXgw4z77WMTu3D4yyD78fTTTF9HKRWnLFFS8zP-CvQ">ht=
tp://tinyurl.com/ycy4pwrc</a>.=0D<br>=0D<br>Mayaro virus (MAYV) is endemic =
in Brazil. It has been found to cause<br>human disease in Par=E1 state and =
in other areas in Brazil. The first<br>report of Mayaro virus cases was in =
1955, in an outbreak in Par=E1<br>state, Brazil. In 2011, thousands of case=
s of Mayaro fever were<br>reported in an outbreak that occurred in Manaus, =
Amazonas, Brazil.=0D<br>=0D<br>As Mod.JT noted in an early ProMED post (201=
10220.0557), MAYV, of the<br>_Alphavirus_ genus, Togaviridae family, is end=
emic in tropical areas<br>of South America (Trinidad, Suriname, French Guya=
na, Brazil, Peru,<br>Bolivia, and Venezuela). In 2016, a MAYV infection occ=
urred in a child<br>in Haiti. The transmission cycle is very similar to tha=
t of the yellow<br>fever virus, using primates as reservoirs and _Haemagogu=
s_ mosquitoes<br>as vectors.=0D<br>=0D<br>MAYV has been associated with a v=
ariety of mosquitoes that are<br>possible vectors that can transmit it to h=
umans. MAYV has been<br>isolated from _Aedes aegypti_ and _Culex quinquefas=
ciatus_ captured in<br>the field in Brazil. _Anopheles_ mosquitoes have bee=
n implicated as<br>important virus vectors (see references below).=0D<br>=0D=
